          "body": "Hezekiah's request for a confirming sign (20:8) has drawn varied assessments in the tradition. Isaiah's immediate offering of a sign — 'Shall the shadow go forward or backward ten steps?' (20:9) — and the fact that it is Hezekiah, not God, who is given the choice between the two options suggests the narrator is showing grace at work accommodating human weakness rather than condemning legitimate desire for assurance. The shadow moving backward on the stairway of Ahaz (20:11) is a reversal of natural order — time running backward as an emblem of death reversed. That the miracle occurs on an object associated with Ahaz, Hezekiah's apostate predecessor who had introduced pagan altar-worship to Jerusalem (2 Kings 16:10-16), is a narrative irony: God redeems even the instruments of faithless reigns for the purposes of His mercy. The sign serves its function within the narrative: it closes the first episode decisively before the second episode (the Babylonian embassy) opens, and it establishes that the same God who controls the stairway's shadow controls the fifteen-year timeline now given to Hezekiah."
