          "body": "The pivot at 20:12 is the chapter's theological climax. Berodach-baladan, king of Babylon, sends envoys ostensibly to congratulate Hezekiah on his recovery — but the geopolitical subtext is transparent: Babylon and Judah shared a common enemy in Assyria, and the Babylonian king was probing for alliances. The narrator's indictment is lodged in a single sentence: 'There was nothing in his house nor in all his dominion that Hezekiah did not show them' (20:13). The absence of any recorded prayer, consultation with God, or prophetic guidance before the display is the chapter's most eloquent silence. The man who turned his face to the wall in private prayer before God (20:2) now throws open every storehouse before the representative of the empire that will plunder those same stores (20:17). The same treasuries God defended against Assyria become, in Hezekiah's hands, a resume of greatness presented to Babylon. Peter Leithart (A Son to Me, 2003) notes that Hezekiah's display is the inverse of the Temple dedication in 1 Kings 8 — Solomon also 'showed' all to foreign visitors, but in the context of directing their attention to God; Hezekiah directs attention to himself."
