          "body": "The chapter's most theologically disturbing verse is 20:19. Hezekiah receives a prophecy of national catastrophe — treasuries plundered, sons enslaved, city destroyed — and calls it 'good' because he calculates it will fall after his death: 'Is it not good, if there will be peace and truth in my days?' The narrator's intrusion into Hezekiah's inner reasoning — 'For he thought' — means the reader is not free to give Hezekiah the benefit of the doubt about his motives. He knows the oracle is catastrophic; he calls it good because it exempts him personally. This is not faith; it is the privatization of shalom. The word shalom, which the prophets use to describe the wholeness of the restored covenant community (Isa 9:6-7; 54:10), is contracted by Hezekiah to personal security. Chuck Swindoll (Hand Me Another Brick, 1978) observes that Hezekiah here illustrates a spiritual failure that afflicts successful people specifically: the horizon narrows in proportion to the achievement. The man who prayed with tears for his own life could not sustain grief for his children's captivity. The chapter ends not on restoration but on this contracted horizon — closed by a royal formula (20:20-21) that records Hezekiah's engineering achievement and his son Manasseh's accession, without the evaluative comment that closure usually brings. The silence is the verdict."
